  "body": "In a ReactJS application I often repeat the following pattern when a component is relying\non a required property  \n\n```\nconst MyComponent = props => {\n  if (!props.user) {\n    return null;\n  }\n\n  return <div>{user.name}</div>;\n};\n\nMyComponent.propTypes = {\n    user: PropTypes.object.isRequired\n}\n```\n\nThe same pattern is [present also in Redux](https://github.com/reactjs/redux/blob/master/examples/async/containers/App.js#L60) and it is the same pattern that the [react-only-if](https://github.com/MicheleBertoli/react-only-if) is trying to centralize. \nBut wouldn't it be clear if a component would just not render without a required property?\nA warning could be still present only in development mode.\n",
